Introduction

In the previous lab we looked at clustering, which is also referred to as unsupervised learning. Now we will take a look at supervised learning. Supervised learning differs from unsupervised learning in the sense these methods take advantage of known classes (the data is labelled). Typically, we separate our data into a training set and a test set. The training set is used for training a model and and the test set is used test if the model generalizes to unknown observations. Supervised learning is also known as machine learning.

Data

Machine learning generally require many observations to be effective, especially when the number of features (typically genes in functional genomics) range in the tens of thousands. We will therefore use cancer data from the fantastic data repository provided by the National Cancer Insitiute in the US. In particular, we will look at data from the The Cancer Genome Atlas (TCGA) Research Network that is producing multi-omics data. We will only use RNA-Seq data in this lab. As many large-scale projects, they have created an R interface to the data - called TCGAbiolinks.

Below there is some code to download read count data. This code takes a looooong time to run, so instead of running the code you should download the count table that the code produces from Canvas: TCGA.RData.

if (!requireNamespace("BiocManager", quietly = TRUE))
  install.packages("BiocManager")
BiocManager::install("TCGAbiolinks")

library(TCGAbiolinks)
library(SummarizedExperiment)

# View all projects
# View(TCGAbiolinks:::getGDCprojects())

counts <- data.frame()
samples <- c()
classes <- c()

# Download RNA-Seq data for selected projects
tissue <- c("Breast", "Kidney", "Colon", "Lung", "Prostate","Lymphocytes", "Skin", "Bladder","Stomach", "Brain","Ovary","Pancreas","Rectum")
proj   <- c("TCGA-BRCA", "TCGA-KIRC", "TCGA-COAD", "TCGA-LUAD", "TCGA-PRAD", "TCGA-DLBC",
            "TCGA-SKCM", "TCGA-BLCA", "TCGA-STAD", "TCGA-GBM", "TCGA-OV", "TCGA-PAAD", "TCGA-READ")
for (i in 1:length(proj)) {
  
  query <- GDCquery(project = proj[i],
                    data.category = "Transcriptome Profiling",
                    data.type = "Gene Expression Quantification",
                    workflow.type = "STAR - Counts")
  
  GDCdownload(query, method = "api", files.per.chunk = 10)
  
  data <- GDCprepare(query, )
  tmp.counts <- assays(data)$unstranded
  tmp.samples <- paste(tissue[i], colData(data)$primary_diagnosis, sep="-")
  
  # Sample must have 20M reads
  idx <- colSums(tmp.counts) > 20E6
  tmp.counts <- tmp.counts[,idx]
  tmp.samples <- tmp.samples[idx]
  
  # Randomly select 200 samples
  if (ncol(tmp.counts) > 200) {
    idx <- sample(1:ncol(tmp.counts), 200)
    tmp.counts <- tmp.counts[,idx]
    tmp.samples <- tmp.samples[idx]
  }
  
  if (nrow(counts) == 0) {
    counts <- tmp.counts
  } else {
    counts <- cbind(counts, tmp.counts)
  }
  samples <- c(samples, tmp.samples)
  classes <- c(classes, rep(tissue[i], length(tmp.samples)))
}
remove(tmp.counts, tmp.samples)
classes <- factor(classes)

table(classes)
dim(counts)

# Filtering
# Genes must have 1024 mapped reads in at least 10 samples
counts <- counts[rowSums(counts > 2^10) > 10,]
dim(counts)

save(counts, classes, file = "TCGA.RData")

A theoretical example of overfitting

[Overfitting][overfitting] is an important concept in machine learning, and it is something that you want to avoid. In the plot below, we have data that is generated by the function

\[y = 3x^3 + 5x^2 + 0.5x + 2 + \epsilon\]

where \(\epsilon\) is an error term. The “real” underlying model is represented by the red line, and a simple linear model (degree 1) by the green line and a complicated (degree 15) model by the blue line. As you can see, the linear model does not explain the data very well. It doesn’t even match our training data, and it won’t work well at all. This can be seen as underfitting. The degree 15 model matches the training data really well, but on the other hand, if we would add more data generated by the function above (test data), it wouldn’t generalize well at all, and is an example of overfitting.

We can divide the dataset into two parts, one for training and one for testing, we can then build the model using the training data and test how well it generalized with the test data. In the figure below we have done this for 15 different models of different complexity (in our case polynomial degree). For each model we plot the mean absolute error for the training and test data (i.e. the mean distance between the points from the dataset and from the model). In addition, we combine this with a 10-fold cross validation (see the next section for more details).

As you can see, the mean absolute error for the training data (black) only gets lower as we increase the model complexity, and that is also reflected in the first plot above. However, for the test data, the error increases after we go past the complexity of the “real” underlying model (i.e. degree 3). Here you can see that the mean absolute error for the training data (red) rises dramatically. This is overfitting. Even if we didn’t know anything about the underlying model we could, from this plot, safely say that we shouldn’t use a model degree higher than 3.

Cross Validation

Cross validation is a method that can be used to test for overfitting. The principle is that you run the classification several times so that each observation has been part of the test set. If you run the cv.ani function in the animation package, you’ll see a simple animation on how a 10-fold cross validation works. OBS: Make sure you have selected the Plots tab in RStudio and run the animation in the Console window.

install.packages("animation")
library(animation)
animation::cv.ani()

In a 10-fold cross validation, as above, you will get a prediction result for each combination of training and test data. The classification error can then be averaged across these results to see how the model performs.

The Caret package

The Caret package provides a uniform interface to a number of different machine learning methods. A typical work flow looks something like this:

  • Use createDataPartition() to divide the data into a training set and a test set.

  • Use train() to train a model on the training set. Typically this includes using cross validation to select so-called hyperparameters. For example, \(k\) in nearest neighbor classifiers is a hyperparameter: training in this case means testing different values for \(k\) using cross validation and selecting the value with the highest accuracy. This value is then used in the final model.

  • Use predict() to predict classes for the observations in the test set, using the final model.

Let’s use Caret to do \(k\)-nearest neighbors supervised learning on the iris-dataset:

\(k\)-Nearest Neighbors (\(k\)-NN)

One very simple, but often surprisingly effective supervised learning method is \(k\)-Nearest Neighbors, or \(k\)-NN. What it does is that for each sample in the test data, it checks the \(k\) nearest neighbors in feature space and assigns the observation to the class that shows up the most among the \(k\) neighbors.

If you run the knn.ani function from the animation package, you can see a small animation on how it works:

animation::knn.ani()

An example using the iris dataset

In the context of the iris dataset, we will train a model that can predict the species of a plant from its sepal and petal lengths and widths. Use View(iris) to remind yourself of the structure of the iris dataset.

Then install the caret package.

First, we’ll need to split the iris dataset into a training and a test set:

library(caret)
set.seed(3)

idxTrain <- createDataPartition(y = iris$Species, p = 0.5, list = FALSE)
iris.train <- iris[idxTrain,]
iris.test <- iris[-idxTrain,]

Now that we have set up the data, we can can train a \(k\)-NN “model”. I write “model” in quotation marks because this method is so simple that it doesn’t really produce a model, but we need to find a good value for the hyperparameter \(k\).

Notice the syntax form = Species ~ ., data = iris.train. This can be read as: “Predict the variable Species using all the other variables in the data set iris.train”.

iris.knn.model <- train(form = Species ~ ., 
                        data = iris.train, 
                        method = "knn",
                        trControl = trainControl(method = "cv"), 
                        tuneGrid = data.frame(k = 2:15))

And finally we can compare the predicted species to the correct species to see how well the classification performed. For this we create a confusion matrix like we did in the previous lab. We can also use the confusion matrix to compute performance measures such as accuracy and error rate:

confusion <- table(iris.test$Species, iris.knn.pred, dnn = c("Real", "Predicted"))
confusion
##             Predicted
## Real         setosa versicolor virginica
##   setosa         25          0         0
##   versicolor      0         25         0
##   virginica       0          1        24
accuracy <- sum(diag(confusion)) / sum(confusion)
accuracy
## [1] 0.9866667
error <- 1 - accuracy
error
## [1] 0.01333333

As you can see, the method performs really well on this data.

Random forest

A popular and powerful machine learning method is Random Forest. This method computes a forest of so called decision trees, each of which combines a set of features (in our case genes) to differentiate the classes.

Each decision tree is computed based on a random subset of observations and tested on the remaining observations. The method therefore contains a built in, repeated division into training and test sets.

Random forest methods can also outputs the importance of each feature: the prediction accuracy of the forest is tested with and without each feature, and the features are then ranked by how important they are for prediction.

Caret also includes a random forest method, but here we will use the popular package randomForest:

An example using the iris dataset

# Install the following package
library(randomForest)

iris.rf.model <-  randomForest(Species ~ .,
                               data = iris,
                               importance=TRUE, 
                               ntree=1000)

confusion <- table(iris$Species, iris.rf.model$predicted, dnn = c("Real", "Predicted"))
confusion
##             Predicted
## Real         setosa versicolor virginica
##   setosa         50          0         0
##   versicolor      0         47         3
##   virginica       0          3        47
accuracy <- sum(diag(confusion)) / sum(confusion)
accuracy
## [1] 0.96
iris.rf.model %>% 
  importance() %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  rownames_to_column(var = "Variables") %>%
  arrange(desc(MeanDecreaseAccuracy)) %>% 
  select(Variables, MeanDecreaseAccuracy)
##      Variables MeanDecreaseAccuracy
## 1 Petal.Length            48.124182
## 2  Petal.Width            47.717498
## 3 Sepal.Length            16.055108
## 4  Sepal.Width             7.648781

Deep learning

Deep learning is a group of machine learning methods that uses multi-layered artificial neural networks. Here we will only look at very simple feed-forward neural networks trained using the backpropagation algorithm.

Let’s look at an example first.

An example using the iris dataset

This is an example of a multi-layered artificial neural networks trained on the iris data:

From the plot: Explain the architecture of the network: how many nodes are in the input layer, hidden layers and output layers? Why?

The architecture of a neural network (hyperparameters: number and size of the hidden layers) is very important for the performance, and finding the right architecture might take a lot of computational resources.

Here we will restrict ourselves to a single hidden layer, and use Caret to find the number of nodes in this layer (using the size-parameter):

# Install package RSNNS, but do not use library(RSNNS) to load it.

iris.mlp.model <- train(Species ~ ., 
                        data = iris.train, 
                        method = "mlp",
                        trControl = trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5),
                        tuneGrid = data.frame(size = 1:10))

Optional: Support vector machines (SVMs)

Another machine learning method is [support vector machines (SVMs)][svm]. An SVM is a non-linear classification method that aims to separate different classes linearly in a higher dimensional space. A simple example could be the following one-dimensional dataset containing two different classes:

There is no way you can draw a single straight line (or more accurately, find a single threshold) that perfectly separates these two classes. However, if we add an extra “artificial” dimension that simply is a transformation of \(x\), i.e. \(y = x^2\), then it is possible to separate the two classes:

This is a very simplified demonstration of what an SVM is trying to achieve with its so-called kernel trick.

An example using the iris dataset

We can use the training and test datasets that we generated earlier using the iris data.

# Install and load the library with svm function
library(e1071)

# Train the model using the training data
iris.svm.model <- svm(Species ~ ., iris.train)

# Use the model to predict the classes for the test data
iris.svm.pred <- predict(iris.svm.model, iris.test)

# Create a confusion matrix
confusion <- table(iris.test$Species, iris.svm.pred, dnn = c("Real", "Predicted"))
confusion
##             Predicted
## Real         setosa versicolor virginica
##   setosa         25          0         0
##   versicolor      0         25         0
##   virginica       0          2        23
# Accuracy
accuracy <- sum(diag(confusion)) / sum(confusion)
accuracy
## [1] 0.9733333
